  <header class="masthead">
    <p class="wordmark">Work with me</p>
    <p class="by">Lee Wilkers</p>
  </header>

  <p>I&rsquo;ve specialized in being a generalist. Some engagements start when a team is trying to figure out a strategy and the situation isn&rsquo;t clear yet. Some start when a program is already running and a team can&rsquo;t tell what is actually happening. Most of my work to date has been in global health and institutional research.</p>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Where I tend to be useful.</strong></p>

  <ul class="judah-aka-list">
    <li>A procedure formally vested with decision-making authority that does not, in fact, produce the decisions. The decisions are produced by a different, unnamed procedure.
      <span class="aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decoupling" rel="noopener">decoupling</a> (Meyer &amp; Rowan, 1977).</span>
    </li>
    <li>A failure distributed across multiple participants such that each can procedurally attribute it to another. The whole has no attributable participant.
      <span class="aka">AKA the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Problem_of_many_hands" rel="noopener">problem of many hands</a> (Thompson, 1980).</span>
    </li>
    <li>An indicator that improves while the encounter, outcome, or relationship it was supposed to protect does not. Naming the divergence is structurally indistinguishable from opposing measurement.
      <span class="aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodhart%27s_law" rel="noopener">Goodhart&rsquo;s law</a> (1975).</span>
    </li>
    <li>A program whose obsolescence is recognized by all parties (including the original funder) but whose discontinuation would require one of them to formally acknowledge the original commitment as a misallocation.
      <span class="aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Escalation_of_commitment" rel="noopener">escalation of commitment</a> (Staw, 1976).</span>
    </li>
    <li>A speaker whose public statement must be defensible rather than accurate. The accurate version is structurally weaker than the defensible one.
      <span class="aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strategic_ambiguity" rel="noopener">strategic ambiguity</a> (Eisenberg, 1984).</span>
    </li>
    <li>A program whose continuity depends on a specific individual. The dependency exists because the individual&rsquo;s contribution was never documented.
      <span class="aka">AKA the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bus_factor" rel="noopener">bus factor</a>.</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Getting started.</strong> If you&rsquo;d like to work together, send me a short or long note about the problem you&rsquo;re working on. I&rsquo;ll ask a few follow-up questions to figure out whether I can be useful before either of us puts time or money down. The more context you share, the better I can prepare. I usually reply within a few days; first calls typically happen within a week or two.</p>

  <p>If you&rsquo;d like to read more before our first call, <a href="/consider-the-tree/">Consider the tree</a> is the longer written version of how I work.</p>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Working with me.</strong> Most engagements start with a paid thought-sparring conversation: <strong>$350 for a 60&ndash;90 minute call</strong>. I send a few prep questions a day or two ahead. The call is where I work out whether I can be useful to your problem, and where you work out whether you want to keep going.</p>

  <p>Within a few days after the call, you get a short written follow-up: what I would actually do, what I would want to know more about, and whether I think I am a fit. If we keep going, we agree scope and rate in writing &mdash; usually a fixed-fee deliverable or an hourly block, your preference.</p>

  <p>If $350 is too much, write anyway. Rate flexes for early-stage or public-interest work. I usually have capacity for one or two new engagements at a time.</p>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Deliverables.</strong> Not every engagement ends in a deliverable. When there is one, it usually takes one of these shapes:</p>

  <ul class="judah-aka-list">
    <li>Synthesis memos (5&ndash;15 pages) on a question your team can&rsquo;t get clean on, usually after several meetings that haven&rsquo;t converged.</li>
    <li>Program audits. What&rsquo;s working, what&rsquo;s reported as working, where the two diverge. Confidential.</li>
    <li>Problem-framing memos for grant proposals, before the drafting starts. Most proposals that fail in writing failed in framing two weeks earlier.</li>
    <li>Workshop facilitation when a team has been stuck on the same disagreement across more than one meeting.</li>
    <li>Draft text. Policy, IRB, protocol, manuscript framing, board memos. I produce the first draft; you take it from there.</li>
  </ul>

